{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/renal-or-ureteric-colic-acute/goals-outcome-measures/qipp-options-for-local-implementation/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"54a60174-eb3f-574f-bb93-5b6f8b5e8d06","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 0ed48b5b-6968-4126-a0bf-f01688850f31 --><h2>QIPP - Options for local implementation</h2><!-- end field 0ed48b5b-6968-4126-a0bf-f01688850f31 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 5f64be6b-1474-4e4f-9331-986d39f9b848 --><!-- begin field 660b8872-11c2-4e21-b9dc-b044d90d477f --><h3>Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs)</h3><ul><li>Review the appropriateness of NSAID prescribing widely and on a routine basis, especially in people who are at higher risk of both gastrointestinal (GI) and cardiovascular (CV) morbidity and mortality (for example, older patients).</li><li>If an NSAID is needed, use ibuprofen (1200 mg a day or less) or naproxen (1000 mg a day or less). Use the lowest effective dose and the shortest duration of treatment necessary to control symptoms.</li><li>Co-prescribe a proton pump inhibitor (PPI) with NSAIDs for people with osteoarthritis, rheumatoid arthritis,Â and think about the use of gastroprotective treatment when prescribing NSAIDs for low back pain, axial spondyloarthritis, psoriatic arthritis and other peripheral spondyloarthritides.</li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/renal-or-ureteric-colic-acute/references/\">NICE, 2018</a>]</p><!-- end field 660b8872-11c2-4e21-b9dc-b044d90d477f --><!-- end item 5f64be6b-1474-4e4f-9331-986d39f9b848 -->","topic":{"id":"cdafd21d-4810-57d3-8f62-82a1a19fdfca","topicId":"a218f6a4-ed45-4224-aff1-78febfb7ee5e","topicName":"Renal or ureteric colic - acute","slug":"renal-or-ureteric-colic-acute","lastRevised":"Last revised in August 2